b4aae\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:55:49.707Z\">3.55pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Farr says he has double-checked and all the other Tpim subjects' passports are with the police.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T16:15:26.690Z\">at 4.15pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824ecce4b0f37bee4ff5b0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:54:48.944Z\">3.54pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Vaz asks about&nbsp;Mohammed Ahmed Mohamed's escape from his Tpim. Vaz says he asked the home secretary whether the police had Mohamed's passport. It turned out she said to the house in good faith that the passport was with the police, but later she wrote to say she had been briefed incorrectly. How was it possible such a mistake could be made, where the home secretary was given incorrect information?</p> <p>Farr says when a Tpim is issued it is standard practice to withdraw the person's passport and give it to the police.</p> <p>An assumption was made that that had happened; the police corrected this, but that was not corrected fast enough in Farr's office, and he apologises for that.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T16:12:57.592Z\">at 4.12pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824e98e4b0f37bee4ff5af\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:52:03.503Z\">3.52pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Farr takes his seat.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52824e7ae4b0f37bee4ff5ae\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:51:45.369Z\">3.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Anderson's evidence session ends. Next up is Charles Farr, director-general of the Office for Security and Counter-terrorism at the Home Office.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52824d01e4b07aa4168b4aac\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:48:07.454Z\">3.48pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Lib Dem Julian Huppert asks if he has suggested to the government his ideas for changing schedule 7 yet. Anderson says he has not yet given the government his &quot;Christmas list&quot;.</p> <p>Huppert asks why the debate over surveillance has been so muted in the UK compared to that in other countries.</p> <p>Anderson says there are two main answers: &quot;Bletchley Park and 007.&quot; Britons are proud of their security services, he says.&nbsp;</p> <p>Plus, he says, we haven't had the sort of bad experience with intelligence services people had in eastern Europe or Nazi Germany.</p> <p>Vaz says 007 shopped at Harrods, but with people escaping from Tpims it looks like now the security services shop at Aldi. (He seems to be suggesting the security services are not as good as they used to be, or are imagined to be.)</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T16:12:15.321Z\">at 4.12pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824b2de4b07aa4168b4aaa\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:43:34.474Z\">3.43pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Winnick asks if he feels that the debate taking place over the oversight of surveillance and the security services has been useful.</p> <p>&quot;I think the debate has undoubtedly been useful,&quot; Anderson says. It is not for him to say whether the damage caused by certain disclosures outweighs this, he says.</p> <p>Certainly one could make the case that the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act is now out of date, he says.</p> <p>Is he basing that remark about damage on any evidence? There doesn't seem to be any evidence of this, Winnick says. In the US a full review is taking place which would not have happened without the Snowden revelations.</p> <p>Anderson says he has not asked for the detailed evidential briefing he would need to be convinced damage had taken place.&nbsp;</p> <p>But he says he can understand the &quot;theory&quot; that terrorists might have used the revelations to change their methods of communication - &quot;it might even be thought to be self-evident&quot;.</p> <p>Is he a Guardian reader, asks Vaz.</p> <p>Anderson replies that it is one of the papers he reads.</p> <p>&quot;It's not yet a criminal offence,&quot; interrupts Winnick, &quot;even to this Tory government.&quot;</p> <p>Vaz asks if terrorists were rubbing their hands with glee at the revelations, as MI6’s Sir John Sawers said at <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/07/heads-of-gchq-mi5-and-mi6-appear-before-intelligence-committee-live\">last week's intelligence and security committee hearing</a>.</p> <p>The spy chiefs have listened to the tapes, and I haven't, so I defer to them, Anderson says.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T16:07:22.279Z\">at 4.07pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824aeae4b0f37bee4ff5aa\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:37:08.612Z\">3.37pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Both Winnick and Anderson refer to the David Miranda case, but not by name, and other cases that are pending.</p> <p>Was the Guardian wrong to publish stories from Snowden's leaks? Anderson says:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I'm certainly not going to get into that. I think we'd all agree that the media are not above the law.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T16:03:55.173Z\">at 4.03pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824acee4b0f37bee4ff5a8\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:36:02.796Z\">3.36pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>But for the detention powers (nine hours is the maximum) perhaps there should be some level of suspicion established, he says.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52824a8ce4b07aa4168b4aa8\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:35:35.725Z\">3.35pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Anderson says we still need a &quot;no-suspicion power&quot; to stop and examine.</p> <p>What if there were two men, one a suspected terrorist, one not? Wouldn't you want to question them both, he asks.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52824a36e4b0f37bee4ff5a7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:34:30.707Z\">3.34pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Winnick asks about Anderson's criticisms of schedule 7 of the Terrorism Act.</p> <p>Anderson says it's a useful power, but it can be used without suspicion on anyone travelling through a port, so there is a potential for overuse, he says.</p> <p>But he has been pleased to see that this power is being used decreasingly.</p> <p>Having said that, there are still 60,000 people stopped at ports.</p> <p>So there is room for further safeguards.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:37:50.211Z\">at 3.37pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824a0ce4b0f37bee4ff5a6\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:33:04.302Z\">3.33pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Anderson points out that Tpims only last two years. That's not a &quot;terrific win&quot; for the police, so for them the first option is usually to prosecute - &quot;and so it should be&quot;.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:37:18.231Z\">at 3.37pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824954e4b07aa4168b4aa6\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:32:10.505Z\">3.32pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Chair Keith Vaz muses that he has lost control of the session a bit; people are asking too many questions.</p> <p>Labour's&nbsp;Yasmin Qureshi asks about the balance between security and civil liberties. Has the balance tipped too far towards security?</p> <p>Anderson says he is rather proud to live in a society where people are broadly safe from terrorism and broadly not too &quot;irritated&quot; by security measures.</p> <p>But although individual breaches of a Tpim - such as being late to check in - can seem trivial, they are very serious offences that people deserve to be convicted for, he says.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:37:04.490Z\">at 3.37pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-528248aae4b07aa4168b4aa4\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:29:16.507Z\">3.29pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Anderson says control orders and Tpims were/are very useful weapons to have in the armoury.&nbsp;</p> <p>But the political storm over escapees may lead to the UK losing this power, he says.&nbsp;</p> <p>Anderson explains why he feels when people come off Tpims they are guided into a better life, whether that is via a &quot;respected imam&quot; or someone else in the community.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:31:19.515Z\">at 3.31pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824804e4b07aa4168b4aa3\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:25:10.342Z\">3.25pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Tory Michael Ellis says there is currently a political row (presumably between Labour and Tories) over whether control orders and Tpims are better. He asks Anderson to confirm that seven people on control orders absconded, and Anderson says that's right.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:26:36.517Z\">at 3.26pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-528247c4e4b0f37bee4ff5a2\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:23:25.009Z\">3.23pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Asked about Tpims coming to an end after two years, Anderson says that before 2005 there was no way to constrain anyone without putting them on trial.&nbsp;</p> <p>The two-year deadline also &quot;concentrates minds&quot; on dealing with the case.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:26:20.004Z\">at 3.26pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-528246c4e4b0f37bee4ff5a1\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:20:33.970Z\">3.20pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Austin asks what extra funds have been provided and what extra surveillance was put in place - considering these two men seemed to escape so easily? Anderson says he could not give the figures. Charles Farr may have the authority to do so, he suggests. But &quot;it's a substantial sum&quot;.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5282462fe4b0f37bee4ff59f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:18:23.577Z\">3.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's Ian Austin says Theresa May said when tpims were introduced that control orders (their predecessors) were excessive and unnecessary. Yet now two people have absconded from them. So was this a deliberate choice to put the civil liberties of terrorism suspects above the risk to the public?</p> <p>Anderson says the thought was if people were freer to associate with acquaintances it might make it more likely the authorities would pick up more information allowing them to prosecute them. Also more money was given to MI5 for surveillance. So the police and MI5 felt there was no substantial increase in risk.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:26:03.189Z\">at 3.26pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5282458ae4b0f37bee4ff59d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:15:50.173Z\">3.15pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's David Winnick recalls how people were held without trial during the second world war. Wouldn't it be better today for people to be tried?</p> <p>Anderson says the best solution in every case is to put people on trial. But the criminal process cannot guarantee to keep everyone safe from terrorism. Out of the 10 people who have been subject to Tpims, four have been tried and acquitted. Nevertheless the home secretary believes they are dangerous and the courts have supported her, he says.</p> <p>He says he is troubled though about this. The inadmissibility of intercept evidence is partly responsible, Anderson says. But the real problem is not wanting to put into open court intelligence from either foreign or UK agencies.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:24:14.302Z\">at 3.24pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824523e4b0f37bee4ff59c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:12:29.287Z\">3.12pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Vaz points out that no one at Mohamed's mosque knew he was on a Tpim - shouldn't the mosque have been brought onside?</p> <p>Anderson agrees the support of communities is the single most important factor in combating terrorism. But people under Tpims don't normally have their identities made public, he says.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:23:31.085Z\">at 3.23pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5282447de4b07aa4168b4a9c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:10:05.587Z\">3.10pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Had&nbsp;Mohammed Ahmed Mohamed come to his attention before?</p> <p>Yes, Anderson knew of him.&nbsp;</p> <p>Is he dangerous? Anderson says the home secretary believes he has been involved in radicalism in Somalia. No court has ever convicted him, though, Anderson points out.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5282443ee4b07aa4168b4a9b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:08:34.676Z\">3.08pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Vaz asks if Tpims are as effective as their predecessors, control orders.</p> <p>Anderson says there are differences; under control orders suspects were &quot;relocated&quot; to other towns, making it more difficult for them to escape.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:10:11.337Z\">at 3.10pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-528243f8e4b0f37bee4ff59a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:07:13.409Z\">3.07pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Anderson says Tpims are not foolproof ways of keeping everybody safe from terrorism. The only way to do that would be to lock up all suspects for ever, and Britain is not that kind of country, he says. Tpims cannot last indefinitely, either.&nbsp;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:09:52.691Z\">at 3.09pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-528243a4e4b0f37bee4ff599\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:06:27.748Z\">3.06pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Vaz begins by asking Anderson about the operation of the terrorism prevention and investigation measures (Tpims) in view of the escape of Mohammed&nbsp;Ahmed&nbsp;Mohammed and&nbsp;Ibrahim Magag.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:09:32.671Z\">at 3.09pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52824388e4b07aa4168b4a9a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:05:03.419Z\">3.05pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Committee chair Keith Vaz notes that this is an ongoing investigation into counter-terrorism.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52824378e4b07aa4168b4a99\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:04:38.645Z\">3.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>David Anderson QC, the independent reviewer of terrorism legislation, is speaking first.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5282436de4b07aa4168b4a98\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T15:04:20.900Z\">3.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The session is beginning and you can watch it live <a href=\"http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=14175\">here</a>.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52823e98e4b0f37bee4ff594\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T14:45:24.568Z\">2.45pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The session has been delayed until 3pm. Apparently the committee is watching a demonstration of electronic tag technology by the G4S private security company. It was G4S who <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/nov/07/terror-suspect-fled-tag-mosque-burqa\">supplied</a> the tag worn by&nbsp;Mohammed Ahmed Mohamed, the terrorism suspect who escaped in a burqa.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/CommonsHomeAffs/statuses/400272073555456001\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>G4S just coming in to give private demo of electronic tag technology. Public evidence will start about 3 pm.</p>— Home Affairs Cttee (@CommonsHomeAffs) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CommonsHomeAffs/statuses/400272073555456001\">November 12, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T14:56:20.697Z\">at 2.56pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52823871e4b0f37bee4ff58f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T14:18:42.769Z\">2.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The home affairs committee session will take place at 2.45pm. These are the two men the committee will take evidence from:</p> <p>• <strong>Charles Farr</strong> is a <a href=\"http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/comment/profiles/article1021573.ece\">former MI6 operative</a> who became a civil servant in 2007. Since then he has been in charge of Prevent, the government’s anti-radicalisation programme, and the surveillance proposals which led to the – now shelved – communications data bill, which would have required phone and internet companies to keep customers’ metadata for 12 months. He is currently director-general of the Office for Security and Counter-terrorism at the Home Office.</p> <p>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/jun/27/terrorism-laws-excessive-reviewer-anderson\"><strong>David Anderson</strong> QC</a> became the government’s independent reviewer of terrorism legislation in 2011.&nbsp;He <a href=\"https://terrorismlegislationreviewer.independent.gov.uk/detention-of-david-miranda-announcement-of-independent-review/\">responded</a> to the detention of then-Guardian journalist Glenn Greenwald’s partner David Miranda in August by saying it was very unusual for someone to be held for the full nine hours under schedule 7 of the Terrorism Act 2000, and announced a review into the matter.&nbsp;He has previously <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-23750289\">warned</a> of the importance of using this power proportionately.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T14:39:58.145Z\">at 2.39pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52821bcee4b07aa4168b4a62\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T12:18:01.109Z\">12.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Europeans and Americans largely oppose their governments spying on their citizens and those of allied countries, a poll found on Tuesday, according to Reuters.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Opposition to government surveillance of private phone and internet data was strongest in Germany, where Edward Snowden's allegations have caused uproar and damaged relations between Berlin and the United States.</p> <p>Seventy per cent of Germans said their government would not be justified in collecting German citizens' phone and internet data to protect national security, according to the poll by the German Marshall Fund of the United States, a US thinktank that promotes cooperation between North America and Europe. Twenty-five per cent of Germans disagreed.</p> <p>Germans were even more hostile to governments collecting the telephone and internet data of people from allied countries, with 72% opposed and 20% in favour. <br />About 1,000 people were polled in each country in early September.</p> <p>In the United States, 54% of people opposed government surveillance of Americans but US views on spying on allied citizens were more ambivalent, with 44% opposed and 33% saying it was justified.</p> <p>In Britain, whose GCHQ eavesdropping agency is alleged to have cooperated closely with the US National Security Agency, 44% said government surveillance of British citizens on national security grounds was unjustified compared to 33% who said it was justified.</p> <p>Forty-three per cent of Britons thought government surveillance of allied citizens was unjustified while 30% believed it to be justified.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-528216c3e4b07aa4168b4a5b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T11:53:56.086Z\">11.53am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Ren&eacute; Obermann, the chief executive of German telecoms company Deutsche Telekom, told a cyber-security conference yesterday that his company was working to keep electronic message traffic from “unnecessarily” crossing the Atlantic, where the NSA could get hold of it, <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/12/world/spying-scandal-alters-us-ties-with-allies-and-raises-talk-of-policy-shift.html\">according to the New York Times</a>.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Other German executives, and some politicians, are beginning to talk of segmenting the Internet, so that they are not reliant on large American firms that by contract or court order allow United States intelligence agencies to delve into their data about phone and Internet usage. Europeans are demanding that any new trade accord include data-privacy protections that the United States is eager to avoid.</p> </blockquote> <p>The paper adds more on the fallout from the revelation that the US monitored the phone of Angela Merkel.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>In the past two weeks, two pairs of senior German officials have visited Washington trying to negotiate a new accord on intelligence sharing that would set ground rules as their government faces its own choice between gently pushing back a protector that has patently played a double game for years, or asserting its power in ways unknown since 1945 ...</p> <p>The attempt to rein in American activity is turning out to be harder than German officials hoped. The early talk that Germany would get the status accorded to Britain, Canada, Australia and New Zealand — just about full sharing of data, and no-spy agreements — has given way to a much more hardheaded discussion.</p> <p>Even German officials concede that a full-fledged accord is unlikely — in part because it would require congressional approval — and that negotiations are more likely to yield a memorandum of understanding.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-528213afe4b0f37bee4ff563\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T11:43:06.477Z\">11.43am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Commons home affairs select committee is chaired by Labour’s <strong>Keith Vaz</strong>.</p> <p>Here are the other members:</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/ian-austin/1511\">Ian Austin</a>&nbsp;</strong>(Labour)</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Nicola-Blackwood/4019\">Nicola Blackwood</a>&nbsp;</strong>(Conservative)</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Mr-James-Clappison/67\">James Clappison</a>&nbsp;</strong>(Conservative)</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Michael-Ellis/4116\">Michael Ellis</a></strong>&nbsp;(Conservative)</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/paul-flynn/545\">Paul Flynn</a></strong>&nbsp;(Labour)</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Lorraine-Fullbrook/4121\">Lorraine Fullbrook</a>&nbsp;</strong>(Conservative)</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Dr-Julian-Huppert/3931\">Julian Huppert</a>&nbsp;</strong>(Liberal Democrat)</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/yasmin-qureshi/3924\">Yasmin Qureshi</a>&nbsp;</strong>(Labour)</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Mark-Reckless/4049\">Mark Reckless</a></strong>&nbsp;(Conservative)</p> <p><strong>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Mr-David-Winnick/316\">David Winnick</a>&nbsp;</strong>(Labour)</p> <p>Both Huppert and Winnick have spoken out forcefully in favour of the Guardian's right to publish the Snowden revelations recently, and criticised the security services for having kept the extent of their surveillance programmes secret.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5281f6bbe4b0f37bee4ff547\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-12T09:38:35.846Z\">9.38am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Welcome to our hub for all Edward Snowden, NSA and GCHQ-related developments around the world, as controversy over revelations leaked by the whistleblower continue to make headlines. As arguments rage over how much of our day to day life should be monitored in the name of security, we'll be tracking the growing global debate about privacy in the digital age. We'd like to know what you think about the whole NSA story, what you're worried about – and any new areas you'd like to read more about.</em></p> <p>At 2.45pm today the Commons home affairs committee will be discussing counter-terrorism with David Anderson QC, the independent reviewer of terrorism legislation, and Charles Farr, the director-general of the Office for Security and Counter-terrorism at the Home Office. I’ll be live-blogging it on this blog, and you’ll be able to <a href=\"http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=14175\">watch it live here</a>. </p> <p>Also today:</p> <p><strong>• World leaders have been understanding about leaked revelations that the US spied on them as they know it was not all done under the orders of Barack Obama, US secretary of state John Kerry has said, as <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/12/john-kerry-world-leaders-understanding-nsa-leaks\">Rowena Mason reports</a>.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>In an interview with the BBC,<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/john-kerry\"> Kerry</a> said foreign governments understood the US president did not personally authorise all the surveillance, which included tapping the mobile phone of the German chancellor, Angela Merkel.</p> <p>Asked about the talks held with foreign leaders over the revelations, Kerry said they had been &quot;very respectful, very understanding. We're all trying to find a way forward that respects<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/privacy\"> privacy</a>, rights, that fights terrorism, that doesn't interfere with people.&quot;</p> <p>Earlier, Kerry acknowledged that the leaders had legitimate questions about the extent of US National Security Agency phone and internet surveillance revealed in stories by the Guardian and other newspapers based on documents leaked by the whistleblower Edward Snowden.</p> <p>There has been public outrage about the spying in some European countries, leading them to demand information from the US about the extent of its spying on its allies.</p> <p>Kerry told the BBC: &quot;The president has ordered a full review into what we're doing. People understand that the president didn't order all these things, this happened over a long period of time, it's been an evolutionary process, we now need to define it more effectively and that's what the president is setting out to do.&quot;</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>•&nbsp;The UK's<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/news/information-commissioner\"> information commissioner</a> has expressed concern about the extent of the<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/nsa\"> NSA</a>'s<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/surveillance\"> surveillance</a> revealed by<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/edward-snowden\"> Edward Snowden</a>, saying that issues of national security cannot be allowed to overshadow concerns of legitimate public interest, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/nov/11/information-commissioner-very-concerned-online-eavesdropping\">reports John Plunkett</a>.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Christopher Graham, head of the independent<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/data-protection\"> data protection</a> body which reports to parliament, told the<a href=\"http://www.societyofeditors.co.uk/page-view.php?pagename=conference\"> Society of Editors' annual conference</a> that he was very concerned by reports of the scale of online eavesdropping but stopped short of criticising the security agencies.</p> <p>&quot;Security cannot trump every other consideration,&quot; he said on Monday. &quot;We don't have that public confidence [in the security services]. That has been the real damage. We have to find a mechanism to bring that back on track.&quot;</p> <p>Liberty's director,<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/shami-chakrabarti\"> Shami Chakrabarti</a>, asked about the impact of the Snowden revelations on the security services' attempts to tackle terrorism, said: &quot;I'm sure it creates challenges and irritations [but] any challenges are probably overblown. The serious bad boys know all about the technological possibilities.&quot;</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>•&nbsp;The Washington politician who is leading efforts to reform US<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/surveillance\"> surveillance</a> practices has warned European politicians that his legislation faces a difficult ride through Congress and resisted calls to expand the law by adding provisions to protect the<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/privacy\"> privacy</a> of foreigners, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/11/sensenbrenner-leahy-nsa-reform-european-parliament\">Dan Roberts reports from Washington</a>.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Representative Jim Sensenbrenner told a meeting of the civil liberties and justice committee of the European parliament to focus hopes on diplomatic negotiations instead – pointing to a key Washington meeting next week, between<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/viviane-reding\"> EU commissioner Viviane Reding</a> and US attorney general Eric Holder.</p> <p>Sensenbrenner's testimony, thought to be the first by a US congressman before a committee of the European parliament, points to the difficulties that reformers in Washington face in assembling a coalition to<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/10/nsa-surveillance-patriot-act-author-bill\"> push reform legislation though Congress</a>.</p> <p>Although recent revelations that the<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/24/nsa-surveillance-world-leaders-calls\"> National Security Agency eavesdropped on foreign leaders</a> have reignited the political debate over surveillance practices, it is not a feature of the key reform bill sponsored by Sensenbrenner and the Democratic Senator Patrick Leahy, which largely focuses on limiting the<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/nsa\"> NSA</a>'s domestic powers to collect bulk data in the US.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• In the first likely structural reform of the National Security Agency<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jun/06/nsa-phone-records-verizon-court-order\"> since the Guardian began publishing Edward Snowden’s revelations</a>, the Obama administration is giving strong consideration to appointing a civilian to run the surveillance apparatus and splitting it from the military command that has been its institutional twin since 2010, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/11/white-house-nsa-civilian-director-reform\">reports Spencer Ackerman in Washington</a>.</strong></p> <p><strong>• The wide distribution of centrally-collated data that allowed NSA contractor access to so many secret documents appeared to be a kneejerk bureaucratic response to the failure of US security and intelligence agencies to share information which, if joined up, should have alerted them to the 9/11 al-Qaida attacks on the US, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/defence-and-security-blog/2013/nov/11/gchq-nsa-leaks\">writes Richard Norton-Taylor</a>.</strong></p> <p>I’ll have live coverage of all developments here throughout the day.</p> </div> </div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/422263300|2013-11-13T15:47:59Z|184fc520a12fd5bd6e9b09d90b8a10987becdb9f -->",
